\layout Abstract

A collection of miscellaneous constants related to various number-theortic
 functions, together with graphs of series involving number-theortic functions.
 
\layout Section

Number-Theortic Series
\layout Standard

Number-theortic series can arise in during the study of fractals.
 This paper reviews Maclaurin series of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}x^{n}$
\end_inset 

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are given by various well-known number number-theortic functions, such
 as Euler's Totient 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(n)$
\end_inset 

, the Moebius funtion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(n)$
\end_inset 

, divisor functions and the like.
 No earth-shattering results are presented; rather, this is a survey intented
 to unveil the general shape of such sums.
 The results are for the most part numeric and consist primarily of graphs.
 
\layout Standard

Note that a general series of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}x^{n}$
\end_inset 

 with a radius of convergence of one can in general be converted to a Dirichlet
 series through integration: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}n^{-s}=\frac{1}{\Gamma(s)}\int_{0}^{\infty}t^{s-1}M(e^{-t})dt\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and conversly ...
\layout Subsection

Euler's Totient Series
\layout Standard

Consider the Maclaurin series
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M_{\Phi}(x)=(1-x)^{2}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x^{n-1}\phi(n)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(n)$
\end_inset 

 is Euler's Totient function.
 A graph of this function appears below.
 The limit of the series as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow1$
\end_inset 

 appears to be 
\begin_inset Formula \[
M_{\phi}(1)=0.60792710185(1)\]

\end_inset 

where the value in parenthesis is the uncertainty in the last digit.
 Other special values (all of which are easy to calculate) include 
\begin_inset Formula \[
2M_{\phi}(1/2)=2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\phi(n)/2^{n}=1.7352616039700447\]

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
3\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\phi(n)/3^{n}=0.698640937680928825\]

\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \[
4\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\phi(n)/4^{n}=0.425655257611738727\]

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
5\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\phi(n)/5^{n}=0.303493769678081032\]

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
M_{\phi}(2/3)=0.527545959546096966\]

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
M_{\phi}(2/5)=0.363055654428664446\]

\end_inset 

 It would be interesting to know what the analytic structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{phi}$
\end_inset 

 is.
 
